The '''Bai language''' (Bai: {{lang|bca|Baip‧ngvp‧zix}}; {{zh|t=白語|s=白语|p=Báiyǔ}}) is a language spoken in [[People's Republic of China|China]], primarily in [[Yunnan]] province, by the [[Bai people]]. The language has over a million speakers and is divided into three or four main [[dialect]]s. Bai syllables are always open, with a rich set of [[vowel]]s and eight [[tone (linguistics)|tones]]. The tones are divided into two groups with [[modal voice|modal]] and non-modal ([[stiff voice|tense]], [[harsh voice|harsh]] or [[murmured voice|breathy]]) phonation. There is a small amount of traditional literature written with Chinese characters, Bowen ({{lang|zh-hans|僰文}}), as well as a number of recent publications printed with a recently standardized system of romanisation using the [[Latin alphabet]].

The origins of Bai have been obscured by intensive Chinese influence of an extended period. Different scholars have proposed that it is an early offshoot or sister language of [[varieties of Chinese|Chinese]], part of the [[Loloish languages|Loloish branch]] or a separate group within the [[Sino-Tibetan languages|Sino-Tibetan]] family.

== Varieties ==
