Xu and Zhao (1984) divided Bai into three dialects, which may actually be distinct languages: [[Jianchuan County|Jianchuan]] (Central), [[Dali City|Dali]] (Southern), and Bijiang (Northern).{{sfn|Wang|2006|p=115}} Bijiang County has since been renamed as [[Lushui County]].{{sfn|Allen|2007|p=6}} Jianchuan and Dali are closely related, and speakers are reported to be able to understand one another after living together for a month.

The more divergent Northern dialects are spoken by about 15,000 Laemae (''{{IPA|lɛ˨˩mɛ˨˩}}'', Lemei, Lama), a clan numbering about 50,000 people who are partly submerged within the [[Lisu people|Lisu]].{{sfn|Bradley|2007|pp=363, 393–394}}
They are now designated as two languages by [[ISO 639-3]]:
* Panyi, spoken by people called ''Lemo'' ({{lang|zh-hans|勒墨}}) on the Nu River (upper [[Salween River|Salween]]) in Lushui county.{{sfn|Wang|2006|p=31}}<ref>{{cite web | title = Change Request Documentation: 2013-006 | given = Eric | surname = Johnson | publisher = ISO 639-3 Registration Authority | year = 2013 | url = https://iso639-3.sil.org/request/2013-006 }}</ref>
* [[Lama language (Bai)|Lama]], spoken by people called ''Lama'' ({{lang|zh-hans|拉玛}})  on the Lancang River (upper [[Mekong]]) in [[Lanping County]] and [[Weixi County]].{{sfn|Wang|2006|p=31}}<ref>{{cite web | title = Change Request Documentation: 2013-007 | given = Eric | surname = Johnson | publisher = ISO 639-3 Registration Authority | year = 2013 | url = https://iso639-3.sil.org/request/2013-007 }}</ref>

Wang Feng (2012)<ref name="Wang2012">Wang Feng [汪锋]. (2012). ''Language Contact and Language Comparison: The Case of Bai'' [语言接触与语言比较:以白语为例 ]. Beijing: Commercial Press [商务印书馆]. 92–94</ref> provides the following classification for 9 Bai dialects:

;Bai 
*Western
**Gongxing ({{lang|zh-hans|共兴}}), [[Lanping County]]
**(''core branch'')
***Enqi ({{lang|zh-hans|恩棋}}), [[Lanping County]]; Jinman (金满), [[Lushui County]]
***Tuoluo ({{lang|zh-hans|妥洛}}), [[Weixi County]]
***Ega ({{lang|zh-hans|俄嘎}}), [[Lushui County]]
*Eastern
**Mazhelong ({{lang|zh-hans|马者龙}}), [[Qiubei County]]
**(''core branch'')
***Jinxing ({{lang|zh-hans|金星}}), [[Jianchuan County]]
***Dashi ({{lang|zh-hans|大石}}), [[Heqing County]]
***Zhoucheng ({{lang|zh-hans|周城}}), [[Dali City]]

Wang (2012)<ref>Wang Feng [王锋]. 2012. A study of the Bai language of Shalang [昆明西山沙朗白语研究]. Beijing: China Social Sciences Academy Press p中国社会科学出版社].</ref> also documents a Bai dialect in Xicun, Dacun Village, Shalang Township, [[Kunming]] City (昆明市沙朗乡大村西村).<ref>http://www.ynszxc.gov.cn/villagePage/vIndex.aspx?departmentid=45388</ref>

==Classification==
The affiliation of Bai is obscured by over two millennia of influence from varieties of Chinese, leaving most of its lexicon related to Chinese etyma of various periods.{{sfn|Norman|2003|pp=73, 75}}
To determine its origin, researchers must first identify and remove from consideration the various layers of [[loanword]]s, and then examine the residue.{{sfn|Ramsey|1987|p=291}}
In his survey of the field, Wang notes that early work was hampered by a lack of data on Bai and uncertainties in the reconstruction of early forms of Chinese.{{sfn|Wang|2005|pp=102–107}}
Recent authors have suggested that Bai is an early offshoot from Chinese, a sister language to Chinese, or more distantly related (though usually still [[Sino-Tibetan]]).{{sfn|Norman|2003|p=73}}{{sfn|Wang|2005|pp=109–116}}

There are different tonal correspondences in the various layers.{{sfn|Lee|Sagart|2008|pp=7–8, 10, 12–13}}
Many words can be identified as later Chinese loans because they display Chinese [[sound change]]s from the last two millennia:{{sfn|Starostin|1995|pp=3–4}}
* [[labiodental consonant|labiodental]] [[fricative consonant|fricative]]s, which developed from earlier labial stops in certain environments.
* [[palatal consonant|palatal]] [[affricate consonant|affricate]]s from earlier [[velar consonant|velar]] stops in palatal environments.
* [[aspirated consonant|aspirated]] stops from earlier voiced stops in words having the [[Middle Chinese]] level tone.
* the initial {{IPA|/l/}}, which developed from [[Old Chinese]] *r-.
Some of these changes date back to the first centuries AD.{{sfn|Starostin|1995|p=4}}

The oldest layer of Bai vocabulary with Chinese cognates, of which Wang lists some 250 words,{{sfn|Wang|2006|pp=205–211}} includes common Bai words that were also common in [[Classical Chinese]], but are not used in modern [[varieties of Chinese]].{{sfn|Gong|2015|p=2}}
Its features have been compared with current ideas on [[Old Chinese phonology]]:
* The voiceless nasals and lateral postulated for Old Chinese are absent,{{sfn|Wang|2006|pp=131, 144}} though in some cases the reflexes match those in western dialects of Han Chinese, rather than those of eastern dialects from which [[Middle Chinese]] and most modern varieties are descended.{{sfn|Gong|2015|p=11}}
* Where Middle Chinese has ''l-'', believed to be a reflex of Old Chinese *r, Bai varieties have {{IPA|j}} before {{IPA|i}}, {{IPA|n}} before a nasal final, and {{IPA|ɣ}} elsewhere.{{sfn|Starostin|1995|p=3}}{{sfn|Wang|2006|p=133}} However, in words where Middle Chinese ''l-'' corresponds to {{IPA|/s/}} in inland [[Min dialects]], Bai often has a stop initial, providing support for Baxter and Sagart's suggestion that such initials derive from clusters.{{sfn|Gong|2015|p=9}}
* Old Chinese *l- generally has similar palatal and dental reflexes in Bai and Middle Chinese, but seems to be preserved in a few Bai words.{{sfn|Starostin|1995|pp=4–5}}
* The Old Chinese finals *-aw and *-u merged in Middle Chinese syllables without a palatal medial by the 4th century AD, but are still distinguished in Bai.{{sfn|Starostin|1995|p=12}}{{sfn|Wang|2005|pp=110–111}}
* Several words with Old Chinese *-ts, which developed to ''-j'' with the departing tone in Middle Chinese, produce tonal reflexes in Bai corresponding to an original stop coda.{{sfn|Starostin|1995|p=2}}
[[Sergei Starostin]] suggests that these facts indicate a split from mainstream Chinese around the 2nd century BC, corresponding to the [[Western Han]] period.{{sfn|Starostin|1995|pp=2, 17}}{{sfn|Wang|2005|p=110}}
Wang argues that a few of the correspondences between his reconstructed Proto-Bai and Old Chinese cannot be explained by the Old Chinese forms, and that Chinese and Bai therefore form a Sino-Bai group.{{sfn|Wang|2006|pp=165–171}}
However, Gong suggests that at least some of these cases can be accounted for by refining the Proto-Bai reconstruction to take account of [[complementary distribution]] within Bai.{{sfn|Gong|2015|pp=4, 7}}

Starostin and [[Zhengzhang Shangfang]] have separately argued that the oldest Chinese layer accounts for all but an insignificant residue of Bai vocabulary, and that Bai is therefore an early branch of Chinese.{{sfn|Wang|2005|pp=110–111}}

On the other hand, Lee and Sagart (1998) argued that the various layers of Chinese vocabulary are loans, and that when they are removed, a significant non-Chinese residue remains, including 15 entries from the 100-word [[Swadesh list]] of basic vocabulary. They suggest that this residue shows similarities with [[Proto-Loloish language|Proto-Loloish]].{{sfn|Lee|Sagart|1998}}
[[James Matisoff]] (2001) argued that the comparison with Loloish is less persuasive when considering other Bai varieties than the Jianchuan dialect used by Lee and Sagart, and that it is safer to consider Bai as an independent branch of Sino-Tibetan, though perhaps close to the neighbouring Loloish.{{sfn|Matisoff|2001|p=39}}
Lee and Sagart (2008) refined their analysis, presenting the residue as a non-Chinese form of Sino-Tibetan, though not necessarily Loloish. They also note that this residue includes the Bai vocabulary relating to pig rearing and rice agriculture.{{sfn|Lee|Sagart|2008}}

Lee and Sagart's analysis has been further discussed by List (2009).{{sfn|List|2009}}
Gong (2015) suggests that the residual layer may be [[Qiangic languages|Qiangic]], pointing out that the Bai, like the Qiang, call themselves "white", whereas the [[Yi people|Lolo]] use "black".{{sfn|Gong|2015|p=2}}

== Phonology ==
The Jianchuan dialect has the following consonants, all of which are restricted to syllable-initial position:{{sfn|Wiersma|2003|p=655}}
