The Gongxing and Tuolou dialects retain an older 3-way distinction for stop and affricate initials between voiceless unaspirated, voiceless aspirated and voiced. In the core eastern group, including the standard form of Dali, the voiced initials have become voiceless unaspirated, while other dialects show partial loss of voicing, conditioned by tone in different ways.{{sfn|Wang|2006|pp=58–72}}

Jianchuan finals comprise:{{sfn|Wiersma|2003|p=655}}
* pure vowels: {{IPA|i}} {{IPA|e}} {{IPA|ɛ}} {{IPA|ɑ}} {{IPA|o}} {{IPA|u}} {{IPA|v̩}} {{IPA|ɯ}}
* diphthongs: {{IPA|ɑo}} {{IPA|iɛ}} {{IPA|iɑ}} {{IPA|io}} {{IPA|iɯ}} {{IPA|ui}} {{IPA|uɛ}} {{IPA|uɑ}}
* triphthong: {{IPA|iɑo}}
All but {{IPA|u}}, {{IPA|ɑo}} and {{IPA|iɑo}} have contrasting [[nasal vowel|nasalized]] variants.
Dali Bai lacks nasal vowels.{{sfn|Wiersma|2003|p=655}}
Some other varieties retain nasal codas instead of nasalization, though only the Gongxing and Tuolou dialects have a contrast between {{IPA|-n}} and {{IPA|-ŋ}}.{{sfn|Wang|2006|pp=32–44, 74}}

Jianchuan has eight tones, divided between those with [[modal voice|modal]] and non-modal [[phonation]].{{sfn|Wiersma|2003|pp=655, 658}}
Some of the western varieties have fewer tones.{{sfn|Wang|2006|pp=32–44}}

== Grammar ==
Bai has a basic syntactic order of subject–verb–object ([[subject–verb–object|SVO]]). However, [[subject–object–verb|SOV]] word order can be found in interrogative and negative sentences.

== Writing system ==
The old Bai script used modified [[Chinese characters]], but its use was limited.{{sfn|Wang|2004|pp=278–279}}
A new script based on the [[Latin alphabet]] was designed in 1958, based on the speech of the urban centre of [[Xiaguan, Dali City|Xiaguan]], even though it was not a typical Southern dialect.{{sfn|Zhou|2012|pp=271, 273}}
The idea of romanization was controversial among Bai elites, and the system saw little use.{{sfn|Zhou|2012|p=110}}
In a renewed attempt in 1982, language planners used the Jianchuan dialect as a base, because it represented an area with a significant population, almost all of whom spoke Bai.
The new script was popular in the Jianchuan area, but was rejected in the more economically advanced area of Dali, which also had the largest number of speakers, albeit living alongside a large number of speakers of Chinese.{{sfn|Zhou|2012|p=273}}{{sfn|Wiersma|2003|pp=653–654}}
The script was revised extensively in 1993 to define two variants, representing Jianchuan and Dali respectively, and has since been more widely used.{{sfn|Zhou|2012|pp=273–274}}{{sfn|Wiersma|2003|p=654}}{{sfn|Wang|2004|p=279}}

