The 1993 revision introduced variants ''ai''/''er'' etc, with the former to be used for Jianchuan Bai and the latter for Dali Bai.{{sfn|Zhou|2012|pp=272–273}}
In Jianchuan, all vowels but ''ao'', ''iao'', ''uo'', ''ou'' and ''iou'' have nasalized counterparts, denoted by a suffixed ''n''.{{sfn|Zhou|2012|p=272}}
Dali Bai lacks nasalized vowels.{{sfn|Wiersma|2003|p=655}}

Suffixed letters indicate tone contours and [[modal voice|modal]] or non-modal phonation.{{sfn|Zhou|2012|p=272}}{{sfn|Wiersma|1990|p=58}}
This was the most radical aspect of the 1993 revision:
