{{Refimprove|date=September 2015}}
A '''tlapitzalli''' is an [[aerophone]] known from [[pre-Columbian]] [[Mesoamerican]] cultures, particularly the [[Aztec]]. It is a form of [[flute]],<ref>{{cite book|last=Horcasitas |first=Fernando |authorlink= |title=Teatro náhuatl: época novohispana y moderna |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YVtXS3wbS6kC&pg=PA164&lpg=PA164&dq=Tlapitzalli&source=bl&ots=BIkkwUX1TA&sig=YaksGVnX23EFJLKXfACejtIhhtU&hl=es-419&sa=X&ei=xedkUI7ACYPW2gWCyICYAg&ved=0CDEQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=Tlapitzalli&f=false |accessdate=27 September 2012 |language= |otros= |edition= |year=2004 |editor= |publisher=[[Universidad Nacional Autónoma de México]] |location=México |isbn=970-32-0878-9 |chapter= |pages=164 |quote= }}</ref> made of ceramic, wood, clay, or bone.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.urban360.com.mx/182063/instrumentos-prehispanicos-conoce-nuestro-legado-musical/|title=Instrumentos prehispánicos, conoce nuestro legado musical|date=2014-12-27|language=es-ES|access-date=2016-09-25}}</ref> They are most often decorated with abstract designs or images of [[Aztec mythology|Aztec deities]]. The tlapitzalli could be multi-chambered, examples using up to four chambers are known. Tlapitzalli was also a term that was used to refer to the [[conch shell]] trumpets used to coordinate attacks during Aztec war ceremonies.
The name comes from the [[Nahuatl language]].
==See also== * [[Music of Mexico]] * [[Latin American music]] * [[Aztec]]
